-- Nigerian Swallows (19)
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Pounded Yam and Vegetable Soup', 'Swallow', 5000, 7000, 50, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Peel the yam, discarding the skin, and rinse thoroughly under cold water. Cut the yam into medium-sized chunks and place in a pot. Add enough water to cover the yam completely, then bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce heat to medium and cook for 25-30 minutes until the yam pieces are fork-tender and easily pierced. Drain the yam through a colander, reserving 1 cup of the cooking water. Transfer the boiled yam to a mortar and begin pounding with a pestle, gradually adding the reserved cooking water a little at a time. Continue pounding, turning the yam repeatedly, until a smooth, stretchy, and elastic dough forms with no visible lumps. Dust your hands with a little water, scoop the pounded yam, and mold it into smooth round balls. For the vegetable soup: wash and finely chop the assorted leafy greens such as ugu and spinach. Blend the tomatoes, scotch bonnet peppers, and onions into a coarse puree. Heat the palm oil in a large pot over medium heat, then saute the sliced onions until translucent. Pour in the blended tomato-pepper mixture and cook for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the raw taste dissipates and the oil begins to float on top. Add the beef, stockfish pieces, and the meat stock, then season with crayfish, salt, and seasoning cubes. Simmer for 15 minutes, then stir in the chopped greens and cook for another 5 minutes until wilted and tender. Adjust seasoning to taste. Serve the smooth pounded yam balls hot on a plate, accompanied by the rich vegetable soup in a separate bowl.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Semovita and Okra Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 35, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Pour the semovita into a mixing bowl and add a small amount of cold water, stirring with a wooden spoon to form a smooth, lump-free paste. Bring 4 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot, then reduce heat to low. Slowly pour the semovita paste into the boiling water while stirring continuously in one direction with a wooden spatula. Once all the paste is incorporated, begin adding dry semovita in small increments, a handful at a time, while stirring vigorously to avoid lumps. Continue until the dough pulls away from the sides of the pot and holds together firmly. Cover the pot tightly and steam on the lowest heat for 5 minutes. Remove the lid, flip the dough over, and stir again for 2 minutes until completely smooth and elastic. For the okra soup: wash fresh okra pods and slice them thinly into small rounds. Heat palm oil in a separate pot, then saute chopped onions until fragrant. Add the sliced okra and stir-fry for 2 minutes until it begins to draw. Pour in the meat stock, add the beef or assorted meat pieces, stockfish, crayfish, seasoning cubes, and salt to taste. Stir in a little water if the soup is too thick and simmer for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally to encourage the okra to release its characteristic draw. Adjust seasoning and serve hot alongside the smooth semovita swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Garri', 'Swallow', 2500, 4000, 10, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 2 cups of water to a rolling boil in a kettle or pot. Place the garri in a heatproof bowl. Slowly pour the hot water over the garri, starting from the center and working outward, until the garri is just moistened and begins to clump. Stir immediately with a wooden spoon or spatula, pressing and turning the mixture until it forms a smooth, cohesive dough with no dry patches. Add a little more hot water if needed, a tablespoon at a time, until the desired consistency is achieved. Turn the garri onto a plate and mold into a smooth round shape with slightly dampened hands. Serve warm as a neutral swallow to accompany any soup of choice.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Fufu and Ogbono Soup', 'Swallow', 4500, 6500, 50, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Peel the cassava and green plantain, removing all skin, and rinse thoroughly. Cut both into medium-sized chunks and place in a pot. Cover with water and boil for 30-40 minutes until very tender. Drain the cassava and plantain, then transfer to a food processor or mortar. Blend or pound until completely smooth and stretchy with no fibrous bits remaining. Transfer the smooth paste to a pot over medium-low heat and stir continuously with a wooden spatula for 5 minutes until the dough thickens further and pulls away from the pot. Remove from heat and shape into smooth balls. For the ogbono soup: grind the ogbono seeds to a fine powder using a dry mill or mortar. Heat palm oil in a pot over medium heat, then add the ground ogbono powder and stir immediately to prevent burning. The ogbono will swell and thicken within a minute. Add the meat stock gradually, stirring to dissolve the ogbono into the liquid. Add the beef pieces, stockfish, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup thickens and becomes drawy and gelatinous. Stir in the chopped ugu leaves, cook for 2 minutes, then remove from heat. Serve the smooth fufu balls hot alongside a generous bowl of the drawy ogbono soup.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Eba and Ogbono', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 40, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 3 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Reduce the heat to low and begin sprinkling the garri evenly across the surface of the hot water in a thin, steady stream. Let the garri sit undisturbed for 1 minute to absorb the water fully. Insert a wooden spatula into the pot and begin stirring vigorously in a circular folding motion, turning the garri into a cohesive dough. Continue stirring and pressing against the sides of the pot until the eba is smooth and elastic with no raw garri visible. Scoop out and mold into a round shape on a plate. For the ogbono soup: grind the ogbono seeds to a fine powder. Heat palm oil in a pot, add the ogbono powder, and stir for 1 minute until it swells and thickens. Gradually add the meat stock, beef pieces, stockfish, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer gently for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup reaches a thick, drawy consistency. Stir in chopped ugu leaves, cook for 2 minutes, then remove from heat. Serve the smooth eba hot with the drawy ogbono soup in a separate bowl.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Masara and Miyan Kuka', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 45, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'In a small bowl, mix the corn flour with 1 cup of cold water, stirring until a smooth, thin paste forms with no lumps. Bring 4 cups of water to a boil in a pot, then reduce heat to medium. Slowly pour the corn flour paste into the boiling water while stirring continuously with a wooden spatula. Keep stirring as the mixture thickens, then add a little dry corn flour in increments while stirring vigorously until the dough becomes thick, stretchy, and pulls away from the pot. Add 2 tablespoons of water, cover the pot, and cook on low heat for 3 minutes. Uncover, stir again until perfectly smooth, then remove from heat. Wet your hands slightly and mold the tuwo into smooth dome-shaped balls. For the miyan kuka: bring the dried beef and meat stock to a simmer in a separate pot. Gradually whisk in the baobab leaf powder a tablespoon at a time, stirring constantly to avoid lumps. The soup will thicken immediately. Stir in ground groundnut, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 10 minutes, adding water as needed to maintain a thick but pourable consistency. Remove from heat and serve alongside the smooth tuwo masara swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Lafun', 'Swallow', 3500, 5500, 25, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 3 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Reduce heat to low and begin adding the cassava flour gradually while stirring constantly with a wooden spatula in a circular motion. Continue adding cassava flour until the mixture thickens into a smooth, stretchy dough that pulls away cleanly from the sides of the pot. If the dough becomes too stiff, add a little hot water and stir to soften. Keep stirring and pressing for 2-3 minutes until no dry flour remains and the lafun is uniformly smooth and elastic. Remove from heat, wet your hands with water, and mold the lafun into smooth round balls. Serve hot as a neutral swallow to pair with any preferred soup such as vegetable soup, okra soup, or ewedu.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Dawa and Okra Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 45, 'gluten-free', 'Nigerian', 'In a bowl, mix the millet flour with 1 cup of cold water, stirring to form a smooth, thin paste. Bring 4 cups of water to a boil in a pot, then pour in the millet paste while stirring continuously. As the mixture thickens, begin adding dry millet flour in small handfuls while stirring vigorously with a wooden spatula. Keep stirring until the dough is thick, stretchy, and pulls away from the pot. Add 2 tablespoons of water, cover the pot, and steam on low heat for 3 minutes. Uncover, stir again until completely smooth, then mold into round shapes with slightly wet hands. For the okra soup: wash the okra pods and slice them into thin rounds. Heat palm oil in a pot over medium heat and saute chopped onions. Add the sliced okra and stir for 2 minutes until it begins to draw. Pour in the meat stock, add beef or assorted meat pieces, stockfish, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 12 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the okra releases its full draw and the soup thickens. Adjust seasoning to taste and serve hot alongside the tuwo dawa swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Pounded Yam and Efo Riro', 'Swallow', 5000, 7000, 45, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Peel the yam, discarding the skin, and rinse thoroughly under cold running water. Cut into medium chunks and place in a pot. Cover with water and boil for 25-30 minutes until the yam is fork-tender and easily pierced. Drain the yam, reserving 1 cup of the cooking water. Transfer the yam to a large mortar and begin pounding with a pestle, adding the reserved water gradually. Pound with steady, forceful strokes, turning and folding the yam repeatedly until it becomes a smooth, stretchy, elastic dough with no lumps. Wet your hands and shape the pounded yam into smooth balls. For the efo riro: blend the tomatoes, scotch bonnet peppers, and onions into a coarse puree. Heat palm oil in a large pot over medium heat and add the locust beans, frying for 1 minute until fragrant. Pour in the blended tomato-pepper mixture and cook for 12 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the sauce reduces and the oil floats to the top. Add the beef pieces, stockfish, crayfish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Pour in a cup of meat stock and simmer for 10 minutes. Wash the spinach or efo tete leaves thoroughly and chop roughly. Stir the greens into the pot, cook for 4 minutes until just wilted, then remove from heat. Serve the pounded yam balls hot with a generous portion of the rich efo riro.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Shinkafa and Bitterleaf Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 50, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Wash the rice thoroughly and place in a pot. Add enough water to cover the rice by 2 inches and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to medium-low and cook for 35-40 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the rice is very soft, overcooked, and beginning to break apart. Mash the rice with a wooden spatula or potato masher directly in the pot, stirring vigorously until it forms a smooth, stretchy, cohesive dough. Continue mashing and stirring for 3-4 minutes until no whole grains remain. Wet your hands with water and shape the tuwo shinkafa into smooth round balls. For the bitterleaf soup: wash the dried or fresh bitterleaf thoroughly in cold water, squeezing and rinsing repeatedly to reduce the bitterness. Cook the cocoyam in boiling water until tender, then peel and pound into a smooth paste. Heat the meat stock in a pot, add the beef pieces, stockfish, and cocoyam paste, stirring until the paste dissolves and thickens the broth. Add the washed bitterleaf, palm oil, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup is thick and the flavors meld. Adjust seasoning and serve hot alongside the tuwo shinkafa swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Wheat Flour Swallow and Banga Soup', 'Swallow', 4500, 6500, 40, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'In a bowl, mix the wheat flour with 1 cup of cold water, stirring to form a smooth paste free of lumps. Bring 4 cups of water to a boil in a pot, then pour in the wheat paste while stirring vigorously with a wooden spatula to prevent lump formation. Cook over medium heat, adding more dry wheat flour in small increments while stirring continuously, until the dough thickens significantly and pulls away from the sides of the pot. Cover and steam on low heat for 5 minutes. Uncover, stir again for 2 minutes until smooth and elastic, then remove from heat and mold into round balls with damp hands. For the banga soup: extract the palm nut juice by boiling palm nut fruit in water and pounding or blending, then straining through a fine sieve. Pour the palm nut extract into a pot and bring to a simmer. Add the oburunbebe stick, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, and the beletete or scent leaves. Add the beef pieces, stockfish, catfish chunks, and crayfish. Season with seasoning cubes and salt. Simmer for 20 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup thickens and the oil rises to the surface. Remove the oburunbebe stick, adjust seasoning, and serve the banga soup hot alongside the smooth wheat flour swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Dawa and Alale Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 45, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'In a bowl, mix the millet flour with 1 cup of cold water to form a smooth paste with no lumps. Bring 4 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot, then pour in the millet paste while stirring continuously with a wooden spatula. As the mixture thickens, gradually add dry millet flour in handfuls while stirring vigorously until the dough is thick, stretchy, and pulls away from the pot sides. Add a splash of water, cover, and steam on low for 3 minutes. Stir again until smooth, then mold into round shapes with wet hands. For the alale soup: wash the alale leaves thoroughly and chop finely. Heat palm oil in a pot over medium heat and saute the diced onions. Add the chopped alale leaves and stir-fry for 3 minutes until wilted. Pour in the meat stock, add beef or assorted meat pieces, stockfish, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup thickens and the greens are tender. Adjust seasoning to taste and serve hot alongside the tuwo dawa swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Lafun and Afang Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 35, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 3 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Reduce heat to low and gradually add the cassava flour while stirring constantly with a wooden spatula in a circular motion. Keep adding cassava flour until the dough becomes smooth, stretchy, and pulls away from the sides of the pot. If too stiff, add a little hot water and stir to soften. Continue stirring for 2-3 minutes until no dry flour remains. Remove from heat, wet your hands, and mold the lafun into smooth round balls. For the afang soup: soak the dried afang leaves in warm water for 10 minutes, then drain and shred finely. Wash the waterleaf and chop into small pieces. Heat palm oil in a pot over medium heat, then saute the diced onions. Add the waterleaf first and stir-fry for 2 minutes. Add the shredded afang leaves, then pour in the meat stock and add the beef pieces, stockfish, periwinkle, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the soup thickens and the afang leaves rehydrate fully. Adjust seasoning and serve hot alongside the lafun swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Eba and Nsala Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 45, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 3 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Reduce heat to low and sprinkle the garri evenly across the surface of the water in a steady, thin stream. Allow the garri to absorb the water undisturbed for 1 minute. Insert a wooden spatula and stir vigorously in a circular folding motion until the dough is smooth, elastic, and free of lumps. Scoop the eba onto a plate and mold into a smooth round shape with damp hands. For the nsala soup: cut the yam into small cubes and set aside. Gut and clean the catfish thoroughly, then cut into medium chunks. In a pot, bring 4 cups of water to a simmer. Add the yam cubes and cook for 10 minutes until soft and beginning to dissolve into the broth, which will naturally thicken the soup. Add the catfish chunks, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 10 minutes until the catfish is cooked through. Wash the uziza leaves, shred them, and stir into the soup. Cook for 2 minutes, then remove from heat. The nsala soup should be light, slightly thickened by the yam, with a tangy and spicy flavor. Serve hot alongside the smooth eba.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Amala and Ewedu', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 35, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 4 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Reduce heat to low and begin adding the yam flour in a steady stream while stirring vigorously with a wooden spatula in a circular motion. Keep adding yam flour and stirring until the dough becomes smooth, dark brown, stretchy, and pulls away from the pot sides. If the dough is too stiff, add a splash of hot water and continue stirring. Cover the pot and let it steam on low heat for 3 minutes. Stir again until completely smooth and elastic. Wet your hands and mold the amala into smooth round balls. For the ewedu: wash the jute leaves thoroughly and pick the leaves from the stems. Bring 2 cups of water to a boil in a pot and add a pinch of potash to help the ewedu soften quickly and draw properly. Add the ewedu leaves and cook for 5-7 minutes until very soft. Add the locust beans and salt. Using a broom whisk or an immersion blender, blend or mash the ewedu until it becomes smooth, slightly drawy, and uniform. Simmer for 2 more minutes, then remove from heat. Serve the amala hot alongside a bowl of the smooth, drawy ewedu soup.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Masara and Miyan Gyada', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 45, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'In a bowl, mix the corn flour with 1 cup of cold water to form a smooth, thin paste. Bring 4 cups of water to a boil in a pot, then pour in the corn flour paste while stirring continuously with a wooden spatula. Keep stirring as the mixture thickens, then add dry corn flour in small increments while stirring vigorously until the dough becomes thick, stretchy, and pulls away from the pot. Add a splash of water, cover, and steam on low heat for 3 minutes. Uncover, stir again until smooth, and mold into round shapes with wet hands. For the miyan gyada: in a separate pot, combine the groundnut paste with 2 cups of meat stock and stir until dissolved. Bring to a gentle simmer over medium heat, stirring constantly to prevent the groundnut paste from burning at the bottom. Add the beef or chicken pieces, pumpkin or spinach leaves chopped, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15-20 minutes, stirring frequently, until the soup thickens to a rich, creamy consistency and the oil from the groundnut rises to the surface. Adjust seasoning to taste and serve hot alongside the tuwo masara swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Fufu and Oha Soup', 'Swallow', 4500, 6500, 50, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Peel the cassava and green plantain, removing all skin, and rinse thoroughly. Cut into medium-sized chunks and place in a pot. Cover with water and boil for 30-40 minutes until both are very tender and easily pierced. Drain, then transfer to a food processor or mortar. Blend or pound until completely smooth and stretchy with no fibrous bits. Transfer the smooth paste to a pot over medium-low heat and stir continuously with a wooden spatula for 5 minutes until the dough thickens further and becomes elastic. Remove from heat and shape into smooth balls. For the oha soup: cook the cocoyam in boiling water until tender, then peel and pound or blend into a smooth paste. In a large pot, heat the palm oil over medium heat and saute the diced onions. Pour in the meat stock and add the beef pieces, stockfish, and the cocoyam paste, stirring until the paste dissolves and thickens the broth. Add the crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 15 minutes. Gently wash the oha leaves, then shred them with your hands. Add the oha leaves to the pot in the last 3 minutes of cooking. Stir gently, remove from heat, and serve hot alongside the smooth fufu balls.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Garri and Groundnut Soup', 'Swallow', 4000, 6000, 35, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Bring 3 cups of water to a rolling boil in a pot. Place the garri in a heatproof bowl and slowly pour the hot water over it, starting from the center and moving outward. Stir immediately with a wooden spoon, pressing and turning until a smooth, elastic dough forms. Add a little more hot water if needed, a tablespoon at a time, until the desired consistency is achieved. Turn onto a plate and mold into a smooth round shape with damp hands. For the groundnut soup: blend the tomatoes, scotch bonnet peppers, and onions into a smooth puree. In a pot, combine the groundnut paste with 3 cups of meat stock and stir until fully dissolved. Bring to a gentle simmer over medium heat, stirring constantly to prevent scorching. Add the tomato-pepper puree, beef pieces, stockfish, crayfish, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 20 minutes, stirring frequently, until the soup thickens to a rich, creamy consistency and the groundnut oil surfaces. Adjust seasoning and serve hot alongside the smooth garri swallow.'),
(gen_random_uuid(), 'Tuwo Shinkafa and Miyan Taushe', 'Swallow', 4500, 6500, 50, 'gluten-free, spicy', 'Nigerian', 'Wash the rice thoroughly and place in a pot. Add enough water to cover by 2 inches and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to medium-low and cook for 35-40 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the rice is very soft and beginning to break apart. Mash the rice directly in the pot using a wooden spatula or potato masher, stirring vigorously until a smooth, stretchy, cohesive dough forms. Continue mashing until no whole grains remain. Wet your hands and shape the tuwo shinkafa into smooth round balls. For the miyan taushe: in a pot, combine the groundnut paste with 3 cups of meat stock and stir until completely dissolved. Bring to a gentle simmer over medium heat, stirring constantly to prevent the paste from burning. Peel and cube the pumpkin, then add it to the pot along with the chopped spinach leaves, beef or chicken pieces, crayfish, chopped scotch bonnet peppers, diced onions, seasoning cubes, and salt. Simmer for 20-25 minutes, stirring frequently, until the pumpkin is tender and the soup thickens to a rich, creamy consistency. The pumpkin should break down slightly, further thickening the soup. Adjust seasoning to taste and serve hot alongside the tuwo shinkafa swallow.'),
